        <section>
          <h2>The 8th Light Blog</h2>
          <p>The 8th Light blog allows for some of the most radical departures in tone, though it also carries an obvious burden of scrutiny and responsibility. Many potential bloggers will view that heightened scrutiny and responsibility as a hindrance, but it should not be. Most barriers to entry are false ones, and are better considered as buffers designed to bring out the best in a blogger.</p>
          <p>The affects of heightened scrutiny and responsibility are byproducts of the heightened visibility. Bloggers are not communicating directly with a client or coworker over a closed channel like email, but are instead communicating directly with anyone who wants to read it. That puts more pressure on the ideas being presented, but oftentimes the thing that causes anxiety is the presentation.</p>
          <p>There are two primary types of blog post: knowledge-oriented and community-oriented. Knowledge-oriented blog posts should be tailored to fit tightly around hard empirical evidence, with less editorialization. Community-oriented blog posts are more open-ended, and allow for more flexibility and editorialization of ideas. They oftentimes are focused around questions that you do not have definite answers to, and you should acknowledge as much when presenting your ideas.</p>
          <p>If you are struggling to write a blog, try breaking your thoughts out into its simplest pieces. Your essay should have an introduction, supporting evidence (usually two or three solid arguments), and a conclusion.</p>
          <p>Start by writing a thesis statement. A standard thesis statement is one sentence that defines your argument and introduces your supporting evidence. For example: 8th Light is a chillplace to work because everyone works hard, everyone is smart, and everyone is friends. In this example, “8th Light is a chill place to work” is the contention, while “everyone works hard,” “everyone is smart,” and “everyone is friends” are the three pieces of supporting evidence that the author will be detailing in the following paragraphs.</p>
          <p>You can continue from there by writing three more paragraphs, each elaborating on a different piece of supporting evidence. This supporting evidence can be unrelated experiences that have helped build your opinion, or they can be steps you followed in order to arrive at your conclusion. Explain why each statement is an argument in favor of your contention. They should be ordered in the same sequence as in the thesis statement.</p>
          <p>The conclusion should summarize your argument, and possibly contain one final revelation that ties the whole piece together. It is not overly important to add new ideas in the conclusion, and doing so can prove distracting if they do not tie together succinctly with the rest of the post.</p>
          <p>At this point you can return to the introductory paragraph, which currently contains just one sentence: the thesis. The thesis is usually the last sentence in an introductory paragraph, and you should build up to the thesis by providing context and defining any terms that may be unknowns. In our example, someone might not know what 8th Light is, or where it is, or what it does.</p>
          <p>Typically, writers start the beginning of the introductory paragraph by employing the inverted pyramid style of writing. Put the most pertinent information about your essay at the beginning: answer the who, what, when, where, why, and how so that the reader is prepared to consume the information that follows. Do not withhold important information early, because there is no guarantee that readers will continue reading past their first impressions. Include any other important information, and then add your thesis.</p>
          <p>Sometimes a blog will not require a full five-paragraph essay format, and that is fine. What is most important is that you establish context, defend your argument using empirical supporting evidence, and then summarize your position in your conclusion.</p>
          <p>In a community-oriented blog post, it is not enough to simply say that you would appreciate feedback. The ability to inspire conversation relies on your writing’s ability to be built by facts, and asserting your interpretation of those facts with humility. When focusing on word choice, be careful to stay within the voice and tone of a humble, inquisitive, and interested contributor.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Writing For The Web</h2>
          <p>While some SEO firms spend time and money on a cat-and-mouse game exploiting quirks in Google’s algorithms, others are avoiding all of the traps with quality content geared toward humans, not machines. Search engines are constantly updating their algorithms to anticipate and punish SEO gimmicks, while rewarding content that serves its readers. The best way to optimize for search engines is to provide quality content that gives readers what they want in an easy-to-find format. Do not use key words to exploit Google analytics; use key words to direct readers’ attention to the content they need. Writing for humans means using clear, concise language, and short, scannable paragraphs whenever possible.</p>
          <p>Link to other content whenever relevant, even if it is not hosted on the same site. This will help the readers discover context on their own, and it will help search engines understand your post’s utility within the larger themes addressed in the post. <span class="end-of-article-marker"><i class="fa fa-dot-circle-o"></i></span></p>
